]]\n| colspan=\"6\" bgcolor=\"{{Plaid Cymru/meta/color}}\" |[[Hywel Williams|H. Williams]]\n|-\n|[[Merionethshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Merionethshire]] / [[Meirionnydd Nant Conwy (UK Parliament constituency)|Meirionnydd Nant Conwy]] (1983) / [[Dwyfor Meirionnydd (UK Parliament constituency)|Dwyfor M]] (2010)\n| bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[Emrys Roberts|E. Roberts]]\n| colspan=\"4\" bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[Thomas William Jones, Baron Maelor|T. Jones]]\n| colspan=\"2\" bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[William Edwards (politician)|Edwards]]\n| colspan=\"5\" bgcolor=\"{{Plaid Cymru/meta/color}}\" |[[Dafydd Elis Thomas|Thomas]]\n| colspan=\"5\" bgcolor=\"{{Plaid Cymru/meta/color}}\" |[[Elfyn Llwyd|Llwyd]]\n| colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"{{Plaid Cymru/meta/color}}\" |[[Liz Saville-Roberts|Saville-Roberts]]\n|-\n|[[Conway (UK Parliament constituency)|Conway]]\n| bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[William Elwyn Edwards Jones|W. Jones]]\n| colspan=\"4\" bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[Peter Thomas, Baron Thomas of Gwydir|Thomas]]\n| bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[Ednyfed Hudson Davies|Davies]]\n| colspan=\"7\" bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[Wyn Roberts, Baron Roberts of Conwy|W. Roberts]]\n| colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[Betty Williams (politician)|B. Williams]]\n| colspan=\"4\" | moved to Clwyd\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Parliamentary constituencies in Wales]]\n\n==Notes and references==\n;References\n{{reflist}}\n;Notes\n{{reflist|group=n}}\n\n{{UK constituencies}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List Of Parliamentary Constituencies In Gwynedd}}\n[[Category:Lists of United Kingdom Parliamentary constituencies in Wales|Gwynedd]]\n[[Category:Gwynedd]]\n", "text_old": "Three '''constituencies''' cover the [[Preserved counties of Wales|preserved county]] of '''Gwynedd''' for the [[House of Commons (UK)|House of Commons]] of the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|UK Parliament]] ([[Palace of Westminster|Westminster]]), and are used also for elections to the [[National Assembly for Wales]]. \nThe current boundaries have been effective since the [[2007 National Assembly for Wales election]] and the [[2010 United Kingdom general election]].<ref>[http://www.opsi.gov.uk/si/si2006/20061041.htm ''The Parliamentary Constituencies and Assembly Electoral Regions (Wales) Order 2006'', OPSI website]</ref>{{refn|group=n|[[County constituencies|county constituencies (CCs) for the purposes of type of returning officer and level of expenses]]; the trivial distinction is sometimes made in the most detailed analyses of UK politics between borough and county constituencies}}.\n\nThe [[Preserved counties of Wales|preserved county]] of Gwynedd shares its name with the southern bulk, the [[Principal areas of Wales|principal area]], Gwynedd, [[Anglesey]] (''Welsh:'' Ynys M\u00f4n), forms a second principal area, i.e. has its own local government council.\n\nFor Welsh Assembly elections, the constituencies each elect one assembly member and are grouped into [[Additional member system|additional-member]] [[National Assembly for Wales constituencies and regions|electoral regions]], in this instance the region is North Wales.\n\n== Westminster boundaries ==\n=== From 2010 ===\n{| border=1 cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\"\n|-\n! bgcolor=\"#ff9999\"| Constituency !! bgcolor=\"#ff9999\"| Boundaries\n|-\n| 1. [[Arfon (UK Parliament constituency)|Arfon CC (Westminster)]] || rowspan=3| [[Image:GwyneddParliamentaryConstituencies2007.svg|left|200px|Parliamentary constituencies in Gwynedd 2010]]\n|-\n| 2. [[Dwyfor Meirionnydd (UK Parliament constituency)|Dwyfor Meirionnydd CC (Westminster)]]\n|-\n| 3. [[Ynys M\u00f4n (UK Parliament constituency)|Ynys M\u00f4n CC (Westminster)]]\n|}\n\n{{legend2|{{Plaid Cymru/meta/color}}|[[Plaid Cymru]] \u20aa|border=1px solid #aaaaaa}}\n{{legend2|{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}|[[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] \u2020|border=1px solid #aaaaaa}}\n{{legend2|{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}|[[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] \u2021|border=1px solid #aaaaaa}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!rowspan=1|Constituency\n!rowspan=1|Electorate\n!rowspan=1|Majority\n!colspan=2 class=unsortable|[[Member of Parliament]]\n!colspan=2 class=unsortable|Nearest opposition\n<!--!rowspan=1 class=unsortable|Electoral wards<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/si/si2007/uksi_20071681_en_4|title=The Parliamentary Constituencies (Wales) Order 2007|publisher=Crown copyright|work=[[Office of Public Sector Information]]|accessdate=7 November 2009|date=13 June 2007}}</ref><ref>[[Boundary Commissions (United Kingdom)|Boundary Commission for Wales]] pp. 1004\u20131007</ref> -->\n!rowspan=1 class=unsortable|Map reference above\n|-\n|Arfon\n|42,215\n|2,781\n|bgcolor={{Plaid Cymru/meta/color}}|&nbsp;\n|[[Hywel Williams]] \u20aa\n|bgcolor={{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}|&nbsp;\n|Steffie Williams Roberts \u2021\n|1\n|-\n|Dwyfor Meirionnydd\n|44,362\n|4,740\n|bgcolor={{Plaid Cymru/meta/color}}|&nbsp;\n|[[Liz Saville-Roberts]] \u20aa\n|bgcolor={{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}|&nbsp;\n|Tomos Davies \u2020\n|2\n|-\n|Ynys M\u00f4n\n|51,925\n|1,968\n|bgcolor={{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}|&nbsp;\n|[[Virginia Crosbie]] \u2020\n|bgcolor={{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}|&nbsp;\n|Mary Roberts \u2021\n|3\n|}\n\n=== 1997 to 2010 ===\n\n{| border=1 cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\"\n|-\n! bgcolor=\"#ff9999\"| Constituency !! bgcolor=\"#ff9999\"| Boundaries\n|-\n| 1. [[Caernarfon (UK Parliament constituency)|Caernarfon CC (Westminster)]] || rowspan=4| [[Image:GwyneddParliamentaryConstituenciesPre2007.png|left|Parliamentary constituencies in Gwynedd pre-2010]]\n|-\n| 2. [[Conwy (UK Parliament constituency)|Conwy CC (Westminster)]] (part)\n|-\n| 3. [[Meirionnydd Nant Conwy (UK Parliament constituency)|Meirionnydd Nant Conwy CC (Westminster)]] (part)\n|-\n| 4. [[Ynys M\u00f4n (UK Parliament constituency)|Ynys M\u00f4n CC (Westminster)]]\n|}\n\n==Changes proposed for 2022==\n\nAs part of the [[Sixth Periodic Review of Westminster constituencies]] the Boundary Commission for Wales proposed changes to almost all the existing Welsh Westminster constituencies, giving their proposals official names in either English or Wales and offering an alternative in the other language.<ref>[http://bcomm-wales.gov.uk/?skip=1&lang=en Final Recommendations 2018] Boundary Commission for Wales]</ref>\n\n*[[Ynys M\u00f4n a Bangor (UK Parliament constituency)|Ynys M\u00f4n a Bangor]]\n*[[Gwynedd (UK Parliament constituency)|Gwynedd]]\n\n== Assembly boundaries ==\n\n=== From 2007 ===\n\n{| border=1 cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\"\n|-\n! bgcolor=\"#ff9999\"| Constituency !! bgcolor=\"#ff9999\"| Assembly region !! bgcolor=\"#ff9999\"| Constituency boundaries\n|-\n| 1. [[Arfon (National Assembly for Wales constituency)|Arfon CC (Assembly)]] || [[North Wales (National Assembly for Wales electoral region)|North Wales]] || rowspan=3| [[Image:GwyneddParliamentaryConstituencies2007.svg|left|200px|Assembly constituencies in Gwynedd 2007]]\n|-\n| 2. [[Dwyfor Meirionnydd (National Assembly for Wales constituency)|Dwyfor Meirionnydd CC (Assembly)]] ||  [[Mid and West Wales (National Assembly for Wales electoral region)|Mid and West Wales]]\n|-\n| 3. [[Ynys M\u00f4n (National Assembly for Wales constituency)|Ynys M\u00f4n CC (Assembly)]] || [[North Wales (National Assembly for Wales electoral region)|North Wales]]\n|}\n\nThe North Wales region also includes seven [[List of Parliamentary constituencies in Clwyd|Clwyd constituencies]].\nThe Mid and West Wales region also includes five [[List of Parliamentary constituencies in Dyfed|Dyfed constituencies]] and two [[List of Parliamentary constituencies in Powys|Powys constituencies]].\n\n=== 1999 to 2007 ===\n\n{| border=1 cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\"\n|-\n! bgcolor=\"#ff9999\"| Constituency !! bgcolor=\"#ff9999\"| Assembly region !! bgcolor=\"#ff9999\"| Constituency boundaries\n|-\n| 1. [[Caernarfon (National Assembly for Wales constituency)|Caernarfon CC (Assembly)]] ||rowspan=2| [[North Wales (National Assembly for Wales electoral region)|North Wales]] || rowspan=4| [[Image:GwyneddParliamentaryConstituenciesPre2007.png|left|Assembly constituencies in Gwynedd pre-2007]]\n|-\n| 2. [[Conwy (National Assembly for Wales constituency)|Conwy CC (Assembly)]] (part)\n|-\n| 3. [[Meirionnydd Nant Conwy (National Assembly for Wales constituency)|Meirionnydd Nant Conwy CC (Assembly)]] (part) || [[Mid and West Wales (National Assembly for Wales electoral region)|Mid and West Wales]]\n|-\n| 4. [[Ynys M\u00f4n (National Assembly for Wales constituency)|Ynys M\u00f4n CC (Assembly)]] || [[North Wales (National Assembly for Wales electoral region)|North Wales]]\n|}\n\n==Historical representation by party==\nBefore 1974 this table covers the historic counties of Anglesey, Carnarvonshire and Merionethshire. A cell marked \u2192 (with a different colour background to the preceding cell) indicates that the previous MP continued to sit under a new party name.\n\n===1832 to 1885===\n{{legend2|{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}|[[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]|border=1px solid #aaaaaa}}\n{{legend2|{{Liberal Party (UK)/meta/color}}|[[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]]|border=1px solid #aaaaaa}}\n{{legend2|{{Peelite/meta/color}}|[[Peelite]]|border=1px solid #aaaaaa}}\n{{legend2|{{Whigs (British political party)/meta/color}}|[[Whigs (British political party)|Whig]]|border=1px solid #aaaaaa}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Constituency\n!1832\n!''33''\n!''33''\n!1835\n!''36''\n!1837\n!1841\n!''46''\n!1847\n!1852\n!1857\n!1859\n!1865\n!''66''\n!1868\n!''70''\n!1874\n!1880\n!''80''\n!''82''\n|-\n|[[Anglesey (UK Parliament constituency)|Anglesey]]\n| colspan=\"5\" bgcolor=\"{{Whigs (British political party)/meta/color}}\" |[[Sir Richard Williams-Bulkeley, 10th Baronet|Williams-Bulkel