{"title_page": "David McCallum", "text_new": "{{other people}}\n{{short description|British actor and musician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = David McCallum\n| image              = David McCallum 2015.jpg\n| caption            = McCallum at the 8th Annual Marine Corps Historic Half (MCHH) in [[Fredericksburg, Virginia|Fredericksburg]], Virginia on 17 May 2015.\n| birth_name         = David Keith McCallum, Jr.\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1933|9|19}}\n| birth_place        = [[Maryhill]], [[Glasgow]], Scotland\n| alma_mater         = [[Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]]\n| occupation         = Actor, musician\n| years_active       = 1947\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{Plainlist|\n* {{marriage|[[Jill Ireland]]<br />|1957|1967|end=div}}\n* {{marriage|Katherine Carpenter<br />|1967}}\n}}\n| known for          = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Illya Kuryakin]] (''[[The Man from U.N.C.L.E.]]'')\n* Steel (''[[Sapphire & Steel]]'')\n* [[List of NCIS characters#Dr. Donald .22Ducky.22 Mallard|Dr.&nbsp;Donald \"Ducky\" Mallard]] (''[[NCIS (TV series)|NCIS]]'')\n}}\n| children           = 5, including [[Val McCallum]]\n| parents            = [[David McCallum Sr.]]<br />Dorothy Dorman\n}}\n'''David Keith McCallum, Jr.''' (born 19 September 1933) is a Scottish\u2013American actor and musician. He first gained recognition in the 1960s for playing secret agent [[Illya Kuryakin]] in the television series ''[[The Man from U.N.C.L.E.]]''.\nIn recent years, McCallum has gained renewed international recognition and popularity for his role as NCIS medical examiner [[List of NCIS characters#Dr. Donald .22Ducky.22 Mallard|Dr.&nbsp;Donald \"Ducky\" Mallard]] in the American television series ''[[NCIS (TV series)|NCIS]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nMcCallum was born September 19, 1933, in [[Maryhill]], [[Glasgow]], the second of two sons of Dorothy Dorman, a cellist, and orchestral violinist [[David McCallum Sr.]] When he was three, his family moved to London for his father to play as concertmaster in the [[London Philharmonic Orchestra]]. Early in the [[Second World War]], he was evacuated back to [[Scotland]], where he lived with his mother at [[Gartocharn]] by [[Loch Lomond]].<ref name=Mail/>\n\nMcCallum won a scholarship to [[University College School]], a boys' independent school in [[Hampstead]], London, where, encouraged by his parents to prepare for a career in music, he played the [[oboe]].<ref name=Mail/> In 1946 he began doing boy voices for the [[BBC]] radio repertory company.<ref name=Mail>{{cite news|last=Swann|first=Yvonne|title=David McCallum: My father sometimes felt I was wasting my life|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/article-1332623/David-McCallum-My-father-felt-I-wasting-life.html|access-date=23 February 2013|newspaper=Daily Mail|date=30 November 2010}}</ref>{{deprecated inline|certain=yes|date=November 2019}} Also involved in local amateur drama, at age 17, he appeared as Oberon in an open-air production of ''[[A Midsummer Night's Dream]]'' with the [[Garden Suburb Theatre|Play and Pageant Union]]. He left school at age 18 and was [[Conscription in the United Kingdom#After 1945|conscripted]] for National Service. He joined the British Army's 3rd Battalion the [[Middlesex Regiment]], which was seconded to the [[Royal West African Frontier Force]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.davidmccallumfansonline.com/sexsymbol.htm|title=Interview from''Motion Picture'' magazine|publisher=Davidmccallumfansonline.com|access-date=15 December 2012}}</ref> In March 1954 he was promoted to [[Lieutenant]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Supplement to the London Gazette|work=[[The London Gazette]]|date=26 March 1954|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/40133/supplement/1882|page=188|access-date=7 January 2016}}</ref> After leaving the army he attended the [[Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]] (also in London), where [[Joan Collins]] was a classmate.<ref name=Mail/>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1951, McCallum became assistant stage manager of the [[Glyndebourne]] Opera Company. He began his acting career doing boy voices for BBC Radio in 1947<ref>{{cite web|first=Yvonne|last=Swann|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/article-1332623/David-McCallum-My-father-felt-I-wasting-life.html|title=David McCallum: My father sometimes felt I was wasting my life &#124; Mail Online |publisher=Dailymail.co.uk|date=30 November 2010|access-date=16 December 2012}}</ref>{{deprecated inline|certain=yes|date=November 2019}} and began taking bit parts in British films from the late 1950s. His first acting role was in ''Whom the Gods Love, Die Young'' playing a doomed royal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vjbooks.com/David-McCallum-s/1772.htm|title=VJ Books Presents David McCallum!|publisher=Vj Books|accessdate=7 January 2016}}</ref> A [[James Dean]]-themed photograph of McCallum caught the attention of the [[Rank Organisation]], who signed him in 1956.<ref name=manfromuncle.org>{{cite web|url=http://www.manfromuncle.org/mccallum.htm|title=U.N.C.L.E. Actor \u2013 David McCallum|publisher=manfromuncle.org|accessdate=7 January 2016}}</ref> However, in an interview with [[Alan Titchmarsh]] broadcast on 3 November 2010, McCallum stated that he had actually held his [[Equity card]] since 1946.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Titmarsh|first1=Alan|title=David on the Alan Titmarsh Show, November 2010|url=http://www.davidmccallumfansonline.com/special.htm|website=McCallumMedia|publisher=Unknown|accessdate=30 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nEarly roles included a juvenile delinquent in ''[[Violent Playground]]'' (1957), an outlaw in ''[[Robbery Under Arms (1957 film)|Robbery Under Arms]]'', (1957) and as junior {{RMS|Titanic}} radio operator [[Harold Bride]] in ''[[A Night to Remember (1958 film)|A Night to Remember]]'' (1958). His first American film was ''[[Freud: The Secret Passion]]'' (1962),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fandango.com/davidmccallum/biographies/p46912|title=David McCallum Biography|publisher=[[Fandango Media|Fandango]]|accessdate=7 January 2016}}</ref> directed by [[John Huston]], which was shortly followed by a role in [[Peter Ustinov]]'s ''[[Billy Budd (film)|Billy Budd]]''. McCallum played [[Lieutenant commander|Lt Cdr]] Eric Ashley-Pitt (a.k.a., \"Dispersal\") in ''[[The Great Escape (film)|The Great Escape]]'', which was released in 1963. He took the role of [[Judas Iscariot]] in 1965's ''[[The Greatest Story Ever Told]]''. Other television roles included two appearances on ''[[The Outer Limits (1963 TV series)|The Outer Limits]]'' and a guest appearance on ''[[Perry Mason (TV series)|Perry Mason]]'' in 1964 as defendant Phillipe Bertain in \"The Case of the Fifty Millionth Frenchman\".\n\n===''The Man from U.N.C.L.E.''===\n[[File:David McCallum as Illya Kuryakin cph.3c35738.jpg|thumb|left|McCallum as Illya Kuryakin]]\n''[[The Man from U.N.C.L.E.]]'', intended as a vehicle for [[Robert Vaughn]], made McCallum into a [[sex symbol]], his [[Cultural impact of the Beatles#Haircut|Beatle]]-style blond haircut providing a trendy contrast to Vaughn's clean-cut appearance. McCallum's role as the mysterious Russian agent [[Illya Kuryakin]] was originally conceived as a peripheral one. McCallum, however, took the opportunity to construct a complex character whose appeal rested largely in what was shadowy and enigmatic about him.<ref name=\"manfromuncle.org\" /> Kuryakin's popularity with the audience and Vaughn's and McCallum's on-screen chemistry were quickly recognized by the producers, and McCallum was elevated to co-star status.\n\nAlthough the show aired at the height of the [[Cold War]], McCallum's Russian alter ego became a pop culture phenomenon. The actor was inundated with fan letters, and a Beatles-like frenzy followed him everywhere he went.<ref name=\"manfromuncle.org\" /> While playing Kuryakin, McCallum received more fan mail than any other actor in [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]'s history, including such popular MGM stars as [[Clark Gable]] and [[Elvis Presley]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.boston.com/ae/tv/articles/2008/11/01/in_the_company_of_spies/?page=2|title=Audiences in the 1960s swooned over the cool men from U.N.C.L.E.|publisher=Boston Globe|first=Mark|last=Feeney|date=2 November 2008|accessdate=2 November 2008}}</ref> Hero worship even led to a record, ''Love Ya, Illya'', performed by [[Alma Cogan]] under the name Angela and the Fans, which was a [[pirate radio]] hit in Britain in 1966. A 1990s rock-rap group from Argentina named itself [[Illya Kuryaki and the Valderramas]] in honour of ''The Man From U.N.C.L.E.'' character.\n\nMcCallum received two [[Emmy Award]] nominations in the course of the show's four-year run (1964\u201368) for playing the intellectual and introvert secret agent.<ref name=\"manfromuncle.org\" />\n\nMcCallum and Vaughn reprised their roles of Kuryakin and Solo in a 1983 TV film, ''[[Return of the Man from U.N.C.L.E.]]''. In 1986 McCallum reunited with Robert Vaughn again in an episode of ''[[The A-Team]]'' entitled \"The Say U.N.C.L.E. Affair\", complete with \"chapter titles\", the word \"affair\" in the title, the phrase \"Open Channel D\", and similar scene transitions.\n\nIn an interview for a retrospective television special, McCallum recounted a visit to the [[White House]] during which, while he was being escorted to meet the U.S. president, a [[United States Secret Service|Secret Service]] agent told him, \"You're the reason I ''got'' this job.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=R_NHKW_2lMI|title=The Man From UNCLE: Behind the Scenes of a TV Classic|publisher=YouTube}|accessdate=7 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n===After ''The Man from U.N.C.L.E.''===\n[[File:David McCallum 1969.JPG|thumb|right|150px|McCallum in 1969]]\nMcCallum never quite repeated the popular success he had gained as Kuryakin until ''NCIS'', though he did become a familiar face on British television in such shows as ''[[Colditz (TV series)|Colditz]]'' (1972\u201374), ''Kidnapped'' (1978), and [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]'s science-fiction series ''[[Sapphire & Steel]]'' (1979\u201382) opposite [[Joanna Lumley]]. In 1975 he played the title character in a short-lived U.S. version of ''[[The Invisible Man (1975 TV series)|The Invisible Man]]''.\n\nMcCallum appeared on stage in Australia in ''[[Run for Your Wife (play)|Run for Your Wife]]'' (1987\u201388), and the production toured the country. Other members of the cast were [[Jack Smethurst]], [[Eric Sykes]] and [[Katy Manning]].\n\nMcCallum played supporting parts in a number of feature films, although he played the title role in the 1968 thriller, ''[[Sol Madrid]]''.\n\nMcCallum starred with [[Diana Rigg]] in the 1989 TV miniseries ''[[Mother Love (TV series)|Mother Love]]''. In 1991 and 1992 McCallum played gambler John Grey, one of the principal characters in the television series ''[[Trainer (TV series)|Trainer]]''.\nHe appeared as a British double agent in a 1989 episode of ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]''.\nIn the 1990s McCallum guest-starred in two U.S. television series. In season 1 of ''[[seaQuest DSV]],'' he appeared as the law-enforcement officer Frank Cobb of the fictional Broken Ridge of the Ausland Confederation, an underwater mining camp off the coast of Australia by the [[Great Barrier Reef]]; he also had a guest-star role in one episode of ''[[Babylon 5]].''\n\nIn 1994, McCallum narrated the acclaimed documentaries ''[[Titanic: The Complete Story]]'' for [[A&E Networks]]. This was the second project about the ''Titanic'' on which he had worked: the first was the 1958 film ''[[A Night to Remember (1958 film)|A Night to Remember]]'', in which he had had a small role.\n\nIn the same year McCallum hosted and narrated the TV special ''Ancient Prophecies''. This special, which was followed soon after by three others, told of people and places historically associated with foretelling the [[Eschatology|end of the world]] and the beginnings of new eras for mankind.\n\n===''NCIS''===\n[[File:DavidMcCallumHWOFOct2012.jpg|thumb|left|150px|McCallum in October 2012.]]\n\nSince 2003 McCallum has starred in the CBS television series ''[[NCIS (TV series)|NCIS]]'' as Dr. Donald \"Ducky\" Mallard, the team's chief medical examiner and one of the show's most popular characters. In Season 2 Episode 13 \"The Meat Puzzle\", NCIS Special Agent [[Caitlin Todd]] ([[Sasha Alexander]]) asks Special Agent [[Leroy Jethro Gibbs]] ([[Mark Harmon]]), \"What did Ducky look like when he was younger?\" and Gibbs replies, \"Illya Kuryakin\".<ref>{{cite episode|title=The Meat Puzzle|episodelink=List of NCIS episodes#ep36|series=NCIS|serieslink=NCIS (TV series)|airdate=8 February 2005|season=2|number=13|minutes=21:37<!--|accessdate=7 January 2016-->}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the behind-the-scenes feature on the 2006 DVD of [[NCIS (TV series)|NCIS]] season 1, McCallum became an expert in forensics to play Mallard, including attending [[medical examiner]] conventions. In the feature, [[Donald P. Bellisario]] says that McCallum's knowledge became so vast that at the time of the interview he was considering making him a technical adviser on the show.\n\nMcCallum appeared at the 21st Annual James Earl Ash Lecture, held 19 May 2005 at the [[Armed Forces Institute of Pathology]], an evening for honouring America's service members. His lecture, \"Reel to Real Forensics\", with Cmdr. Craig T. Mallak, U.S. Armed Forces medical examiner, featured a presentation comparing the real-life work of the Armed Forces Medical Examiner staff with that of the fictional naval investigators appearing on ''NCIS''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.davidmccallumfansonline.com/afip.htm|title=David McCallum discusses medical examiner work|publisher=Davidmccallumfansonline.com|date=27 May 2005|accessdate=25 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn late April 2012 it was announced that McCallum had reached agreement on a two-year contract extension with CBS-TV. The move meant that he would remain an ''NCIS'' regular past his eightieth birthday.<ref>{{cite web|last=Eng|first=Joyce|url=https://www.tvguide.com/News/David-McCallum-NCIS-Contract-1046752.aspx|title=David McCallum re-ups NCIS contract|publisher=TV Guide.com|date=30 April 2012|accessdate=30 April 2012}}</ref>\nIn May 2014 he signed another two-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zap2it.com/blogs/ncis_season_12_and_13_sean_murray_pauley_perrette_david_mccallum_rocky_carroll_sign_new_2-year_deals-2014-05|work=[[Zap2it]]|date=5 May 2014|accessdate=7 January 2016|publisher=[[Tribune Media]]|first=Sydney|last=Bucksbaum|title='NCIS' Season 12 and 13: Sean Murray, Pauley Perrette, David McCallum, Rocky Carroll sign new 2-year deals}}</ref> He has since signed extensions in 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inquisitr.com/3243205/ncis-cast-news-sean-murray-pauley-perrette-david-mccallum-rocky-carroll-signed-seasons-14-and-15/\n|work=[[Inquisitr]]|date=25 June 2016|accessdate=9 May 2018|publisher=[[The Inquisitr]]|first=Nicole|last=Giacobone\n|title=\u2018NCIS\u2019 Cast News: Sean Murray, Pauley Perrette, David McCallum, And Rocky Carroll Signed For Seasons 14 And 15}}</ref>  beginning a limited schedule in 2017 and renewing the same for seasons 15, 16 & 17 - each one separately.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/05/ncis-david-mccallum-return-season-16-cbs-series-ducky-mallard-1202382769/|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=4 May 2018|accessdate=9 May 2018|publisher=[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]]|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva\n|title=\u2018NCIS\u2019: David McCallum Set To Return For Season 16 Of CBS Series}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\nIn the 1960s, McCallum recorded four albums for [[Capitol Records]] with music producer [[David Axelrod (musician)|David Axelrod]]: ''Music...A Part of Me'' (Capitol ST 2432, 1966), ''Music...A Bit More of Me'' (Capitol ST 2498, 1966), ''Music...It's Happening Now!'' (Capitol ST 2651, 1967), and ''McCallum'' (Capitol ST 2748, 1968). The best known of his pieces today is \"The Edge\", which was sampled by [[Dr. Dre]] as the intro and riff to the track \"[[The Next Episode]]\", \"M.I.A\" by Missin' Linx, and \"No Regrets\" by [[Masta Ace]]. McCallum's version of \"The Edge\" appears on the soundtrack to the 2017 film [[Baby Driver]].\n\nMcCallum did not sing on these records, as many television stars of the 1960s did when offered recording contracts. As a classically trained musician, he conceived a blend of oboe, English horn and strings with guitar and drums, and presented instrumental interpretations of hits of the day. The official arranger on the albums was H. B. Barnum. However, McCallum conducted, and contributed several original compositions of his own, over the course of four LPs. The first two, ''Music...A Part of Me'' and ''Music...A Bit More of Me'', have been issued together on CD on the Zonophone label. On ''Open Channel D'', McCallum did sing on the first four tracks, \"Communication\", \"House on Breckenridge Lane\", \"In the Garden, Under the Tree\" (the theme song from the film ''Three Bites of the Apple'') and \"My Carousel\". The music tracks are the same as the Zonophone CD. This CD was released on the Rev-Ola label. The [[single (music)|single]] release of \"Communication\" reached No. 32 in the [[UK Singles Chart]] in April 1966.<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book|first=David|last=Roberts|year=2006|title=[[British Hit Singles & Albums]]|edition=19th|publisher=Guinness World Records Limited|location= London|isbn=1-904994-10-5|page= 337}}</ref>\n\nIn the ''[[The Man from U.N.C.L.E.|Man from U.N.C.L.E.]]'' episode \"The Discotheque Affair\", McCallum plays the double bass as part of a band in a night club. He also played guitar and sang his own composition, \"Trouble,\" with Nancy Sinatra on \"The Take Me to Your Leader Affair,\" and played several instruments in \"The Off-Broadway Affair\".\n\nIn the 1970s, McCallum also recorded three H.P. Lovecraft tales for Caedmon Records, an imprint of August Derleth's Arkham House publishing venture: \"The Rats in the Walls\" (TC 1347, 1973); \"The Dunwich Horror\" (\"slightly abridged\"; TC 1467, 1976); and \"The Haunter of the Dark\" (TC 1617, 1979).\n\n===Fiction===\nIn 2016, McCallum published a crime novel entitled ''Once a Crooked Man''. The narrative is set in New York and London and centres on a young actor who tries to foil a murder.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/books/at-82-ncis-actor-david-mccallum-has-written-a-delicious-crime-caper/2016/01/11/b71995fa-b872-11e5-829c-26ffb874a18d_story.html|title=At 82, \u2018NCIS\u2019 actor David McCallum has written a delicious crime caper|first1=Neely|last1=Tucker|first2=Neely|last2=Tucker|date=11 January 2016|access-date=31 August 2017|via=WashingtonPost.com}}</ref> McCallum has stated that a second novel is in progress.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/arts_ents/14193287.Why_Man_from_U_N_C_L_E_star_David_McCallum_is_learning_new_lines/|title=Why Man from U.N.C.L.E star David McCallum is learning new lines|website=HeraldScotland|access-date=31 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOn 11 May 1957, McCallum  married actress [[Jill Ireland]] in London. The couple had met during production of the film ''[[Hell Drivers (film)|Hell Drivers]]''. The marriage lasted 10 years. After leaving McCallum, Ireland married [[Charles Bronson]], whom McCallum had introduced to her while McCallum and Bronson were filming ''[[The Great Escape (film)|The Great Escape]]'' (1963). McCallum and Ireland had three sons: Paul, Jason and Valentine (Val). Jason, who was adopted, died from an accidental drug overdose in 1989.<ref name=\"People\" /> [[Val McCallum]] is a guitar player, playing with [[Jackson Browne]] most recently in 2014 and is a member of the faux country band, Jackshit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://popcultureblog.dallasnews.com/2014/07/at-65-jackson-browne-continues-to-rock-and-roll-announcing-an-international-tour-and-a-new-studio-album.html/|title=At 65, Jackson Browne continues to rock and roll, announcing a new album and world tour|access-date=25 July 2015|date=18 July 2014|first=Michael|last=Granberry|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304103132/http://popcultureblog.dallasnews.com/2014/07/at-65-jackson-browne-continues-to-rock-and-roll-announcing-an-international-tour-and-a-new-studio-album.html/|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Lisa Respers |url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/SHOWBIZ/TV/02/03/david.mccallum.ncis/index.html?imw=Y&iref=mpstoryemail|title='NCIS' actor's portrayal is dead on|publisher=CNN.com|date=3 February 2009|access-date=16 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 1967, McCallum married Katherine Carpenter. They have a son, Peter, and a daughter, Sophie. McCallum and his wife are active in charitable organisations that support the [[United States Marine Corps]]: Katherine's father was a Marine who served in the [[Battle of Iwo Jima]] and her brother was killed in the [[Vietnam War]]. On 27 August 1999, McCallum was naturalized as a United States citizen.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/DavidMcCallumWriter/photos/a.107091362972150.1073741828.101763950171558/124520094562610/?type=3&theater|title=Celebrating the date I became an American citizen|access-date=22 May 2017|date=28 August 2015|first=David|last=McCallum}}</ref> McCallum has six grandchildren. He was friends with [[Tibor Rubin]].<ref name=\"People\">{{cite web|url=http://www.people.co.uk/celebs-tv/celebrity-interview/2010/06/27/david-mcallum-s-heartache-at-death-of-adopted-son-102039-22363142/ |title=David Mcallum's heartache at death of adopted son \u2013 Celebrity Interview \u2013 Celebs + TV|publisher=People.co.uk|date=27 June 2010|access-date=16 December 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Local Hero Honored For Service In Korean War|url=http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2014/08/08/local-hero-honored-for-service-in-korean-war/|accessdate=17 May 2018|publisher=CBS Los Angeles|date=8 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" | 1957\n| ''[[Ill Met by Moonlight (film)|Ill Met By Moonlight]]''\n| Sailor\n| {{Plainlist|\n* Film debut\n* [[Cameo appearance|Uncredited]]\n* Also known as ''Night Ambush''\n}}\n|-\n| ''[[These Dangerous Years]]''\n| \n| Also known as ''Dangerous Youth''\n|-\n| ''[[Robbery Under Arms (1957 film)|Robbery Under Arms]]''\n| Jim Marston\n| British [[Crime film]]\n|-\n| ''[[Hell Drivers (film)|Hell Drivers]]''\n| Jimmy Yately\n| Directed by [[Cy Endfield]]\n|-\n| ''[[The Secret Place (film)|The Secret Place]]''\n| Mike Wilson\n| Directorial debut of [[Clive Donner]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1958\n| ''[[A Night to Remember (1958 film)|A Night to Remember]]''\n| [[Harold Bride]]\n| Iconic British drama about the sinking of [[RMS Titanic]]\n|-\n| ''[[Violent Playground]]''\n| Johnnie Murphy\n| Directed by [[Basil Dearden]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1961\n| ''[[The Long and the Short and the Tall (film)|The Long and the Short and the Tall]]''\n| Private Samuel \"Sammy\" Whitaker\n| Released as ''Jungle Fighters'' in the US and Canada\n|-\n| ''[[Jungle Street]]''\n| Terry Collins\n| Later retitled  ''Jungle Street Girls''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1962\n| ''[[Freud: The Secret Passion]]''\n| Carl von Schlossen\n| Also known as ''Freud''\n|-\n| ''[[Billy Budd (film)|Billy Budd]]''\n| Steven Wyatt\n| A [[CinemaScope]] film produced, directed, and co-written by [[Peter Ustinov]]\n|-\n| 1963\n| ''[[The Great Escape (film)|The Great Escape]]''\n| Lt. Cmdr. Eric Ashley-Pitt, \"Dispersal\"\n| Based on an escape by British and [[Commonwealth]] [[prisoner of war|prisoners of war]] from a [[Stalag|German POW camp]] during the [[Second World War]]\n|-\n| 1964\n| ''[[To Trap a Spy]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Illya Kuryakin]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | A ''[[The Man from U.N.C.L.E.|Man from U.N.C.L.E.]]'' film\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1965\n| ''[[The Spy with My Face]]''\n|-\n| ''[[The Greatest Story Ever Told]]''\n| [[Judas Iscariot]]\n| Retelling of the story of [[Jesus]], from the [[Nativity of Jesus|Nativity]] through the [[Resurrection of Jesus|Resurrection]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" | 1966\n| ''[[One Spy Too Many]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Illya Kuryakin\n| rowspan=\"2\" | A ''Man from U.N.C.L.E.'' film\n|-\n| ''[[The Spy in the Green Hat]]''\n|-\n| ''[[Around the World Under the Sea]]''\n| Dr. Philip Volker\n| \n|-\n| ''[[The Big T.N.T. Show]]''\n| Master of Ceremonies, conducting the orchestra\n| \"(I Can't Get No) Satisfaction\" (instrumental)\n|-\n| ''[[One of Our Spies Is Missing]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Illya Kuryakin\n| rowspan=\"2\" | A ''Man from U.N.C.L.E.'' film\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1967\n| ''[[The Karate Killers]]''\n|-\n| ''[[Three Bites of the Apple]]''\n| Stanley Thrumm\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 1968\n| ''[[The Helicopter Spies]]''\n| Illya Kuryakin\n| A ''Man from U.N.C.L.E.'' film\n|-\n| ''[[Sol Madrid]]''\n| Sol Madrid\n| Released in the UK as ''The Heroin Gang''\n|-\n| ''[[How to Steal the World]]''\n| Illya Kuryakin\n| A ''Man From U.N.C.L.E.'' film\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 1969\n| ''[[Mosquito Squadron]]''\n| Squadron Leader Quint Monroe, [[Royal Canadian Air Force|RCAF]]\n| British [[war film]]\n|-\n| ''[[The Ravine]]''\n| Sergeant Stephen Holmann\n| Italian-Yugoslav-American war film\n|-\n| ''[[Rascal (film)|Rascal]]''\n| Ice Cream Man\n| {{Plainlist|\n* [[Comedy-drama]] [[Film adaptation|film adaption]] made by [[Walt Disney Pictures|Walt Disney Productions]]\n* Based on a book ''[[Rascal (book)|Rascal]]'' by [[Sterling North]]\n}}\n|- \n| 1972\n| ''She Waits''\n| Mark Wilson\n| [[Horror film]]\n|-\n| 1975\n| ''[[The Kingfisher Caper]]''\n| Benedict Van Der Byl\n| Released as ''Diamond Hunters'' in South Africa and as ''Diamond Lust'' on video\n|-\n| 1976\n| ''[[Dogs (1976 film)|Dogs]]''\n| Harlan Thompson\n| \n|-\n| 1977\n| ''[[King Solomon's Treasure]]''\n| Sir Henry Curtis\n| British-Canadian [[low-budget film]] based on the novel ''[[King Solomon's Mines]]''\n|-\n| 1980\n| ''[[The Watcher in the Woods (1980 film)|The Watcher in the Woods]]''\n| Paul Curtis\n| {{Plainlist|\n* [[Cinema of the United States|American]] [[Children's film|family]] [[fantasy film|fantasy]] [[Thriller film|thriller]] film\n* Based on the [[A Watcher in the Woods|1976 novel]] by Florence Engel Randall\n}}\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''Terminal Choice''\n| Dr. Giles Dodson\n| \n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[The Wind (1986 film)|The Wind]]''\n| John\n| Released in 1987 in the USA\n|-\n| 1990\n| ''[[The Haunting of Morella]]''\n| Gideon\n| Set in [[Colonial history of the United States|colonial America]]\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''[[Hear My Song]]''\n| Jim Abbott\n| \n|-\n| 1993\n| ''Fatal Inheritance''\n| Brandon Murphy\n| \n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[Dirty Weekend (1993 film)|Dirty Weekend]]''\n| Reggie\n| Based on the [[Dirty Weekend (novel)|novel of the same name]] by [[Helen Zahavi]]\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''[[Healer (film)|Healer]]''\n| The Jackal\n| \n|-\n| 1999\n| ''Cherry''\n| Mammy\n| \n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Batman: Gotham Knight]]''\n| [[Alfred Pennyworth]] (voice)\n| rowspan=\"4\" | [[Direct-to-video]]\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Wonder Woman (2009 film)|Wonder Woman]]''\n| [[Zeus (DC Comics)|Zeus]] (voice)\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Son of Batman]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Alfred Pennyworth (voice)\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Batman vs. Robin]]''\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1959 \n| ''[[Anouilh's Antigone]]'' \n| Haemon\n|-\n| 1961\n| ''[[Sir Francis Drake (TV series)|Sir Francis Drake]]''\n| Lord Oakshott\n| Episode: \"The English Dragon\" (S 1:Ep 6)\n|-\n| 1963\n| ''[[The Outer Limits (1963 TV series)|The Outer Limits]]''\n| Gwyllm Griffiths\n| Episode: \"[[The Sixth Finger]]\" (S 1:Ep 5)\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" | 1964\n| ''[[The Travels of Jaimie McPheeters (TV series)|The Travels of Jaimie McPheeters]]''\n| Prophet\n| Episode: \"The Day Of The Search\" (S 1:Ep 18)\n|-\n| ''[[Perry Mason (TV series)|Perry Mason]]''\n| Phillipe Bertain\n| Episode: \"The Case of the Fifty-Millionth Frenchman\" (S 7:Ep 19)\n|-\n| ''[[The Great Adventure (U.S. TV series)|The Great Adventure]]''\n| Captain Hanning\n| Episodes: {{Plainlist|\n* \"Kentucky's Bloody Ground\" (S 1:Ep 23)\n* \"The Siege of Boonesborough\" (S 1:Ep 24)\n}}\n|-\n| ''The Outer Limits''\n| Tone Hobart\n| Episode: \"[[The Forms of Things Unknown]]\" (S 1:Ep 32)\n|-\n| ''[[Profiles in Courage (TV series)|Profiles in Courage]]''\n| [[John Adams]]\n| Episode: \"John Adams\" (S 1:Ep 7)\n|-\n| 1964\u201368\n| ''[[The Man from U.N.C.L.E.]]''\n| [[Illya Kuryakin]]\n| Main cast\n|-\n| 1965\n| ''[[Hullabaloo (TV series)|Hullabaloo]]''\n| Host\n| {{Plainlist|\n* Credited as Dave McCallum\n* Episode: \"Show 21\" (S 2:Ep 21)\n}}\n|-\n| 1966\n| ''[[Please Don't Eat the Daisies (TV series)|Please Don't Eat the Daisies]]''\n| Illya Kuryakin\n| Episode: \"Say U.N.C.L.E.\" (S 1:Ep 18)\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |1969\n| ''[[Hallmark Hall of Fame]]''\n| Hamilton Cade\n| Episode: \"Teacher, Teacher\" (S 18:Ep 3)\n|-\n| ''[[Hallmark Hall of Fame]]''\n| Kenneth Canfield\n| Episode: \"The File On Devlin\" (S 19:Ep 1)\n|-\n| 1970\n| ''[[Hauser's Memory]]''\n| Hillel Mondoro\n| {{Plainlist|\n* [[science fiction film|Science fiction television film]]\n* Screenplay by [[Adrian Spies]] was based on a 1968 novel of the same name which was a sequel to the novel ''[[Donovan's Brain]]''.\n}}\n|-\n| 1971\n| ''[[Night Gallery]]''\n| Dr. Joel Winter\n| Episode: \"The Phantom Farmhouse\" (S 2:Ep 16)\n|-\n| 1971\n| ''[[The Man and the City]]''\n| {{cGuest}}\n| Episode: \"Pipe Me A Loving Tune\" (S 1:Ep 12)\n|-\n| 1972\u201374\n| ''[[Colditz (TV series)|Colditz]]''\n| Simon Carter\n| Main cast\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1973\n| ''[[Frankenstein: The True Story]]''\n| Dr. Henry Clerval\n| Made for TV film\n|-\n| ''[[The Six Million Dollar Man]]''\n| Alexi Kaslov\n| Episode: \"Wine, Women and War\" (S 1:Ep 3)\n|-\n| 1975\u201376\n| ''[[The Invisible Man (1975 T